text:
Who This Book Is For
This book is aimed at:

engineers building question-answering, assistant, search, or knowledge tools;
data and ML practitioners who need a clear end-to-end view of the stack;
product teams deciding when RAG is a better fit than fine-tuning or manual workflows;
learners who want a grounded mental model before choosing frameworks.

You can read the book from start to finish, but each major chapter is also designed to stand on its own as a reference.

What You Will Learn
By the end of this book, you should be able to:

explain what RAG is and when it is useful;
prepare and structure data for retrieval;
choose embedding, indexing, and vector storage strategies;
design dense, sparse, hybrid, and structured retrieval flows;
turn retrieved evidence into grounded answers;
evaluate retrieval quality, grounding, and answer quality;
understand where advanced architectures such as graph-augmented RAG fit.

1.3 Core Principles and System Architecture
A practical RAG system usually contains the following components:

a data pipeline that ingests documents, records, or events;
a transformation layer that cleans, chunks, and annotates content;
an indexing layer that stores vectors, tokens, or structured fields;
a retrieval layer that selects candidate evidence;
a ranking layer that orders or filters candidates;
a generation layer that produces the final answer;
an evaluation and observability layer that measures quality.

You do not need to memorize this list on first read. The important point is simpler: errors compound across layers. If chunking is poor, retrieval quality suffers. If retrieval is weak, prompting cannot rescue grounding. If evaluation is absent, teams often optimize for style instead of correctness.

1.5 When to Use RAG: Use Cases and Risk Levels
RAG is especially useful in:

enterprise knowledge assistants;
customer support copilots;
legal and policy lookup tools;
research and synthesis systems;
analytics assistants backed by tables or warehouses;
multimodal search over documents, images, or media.

Risk level matters. In low-risk settings, approximate retrieval may be acceptable. In high-risk settings such as healthcare, legal review, or compliance, the system needs stricter grounding, stronger auditability, and explicit fallbacks when evidence is weak.

1.7 Evaluation Challenges and Optimization Directions
RAG systems are difficult to evaluate because the output quality depends on both retrieval quality and generation quality. A weak answer may come from poor evidence, poor prompt design, or both. That means metrics need to separate stages whenever possible.
Optimization typically moves along these axes:

improve corpus coverage;
improve chunking and metadata;
improve embedding/index selection;
improve candidate ranking and filtering;
improve prompt structure and answer constraints;
reduce latency and token cost.

2.5 Document Loaders and Processing Tools
Document loaders are useful because each source format fails in different ways. PDFs may have broken reading order. HTML may include navigation chrome. Spreadsheets may hide semantics in headers. OCR pipelines may introduce noise.
A robust processing stack usually includes:

format-specific loaders;
content validators;
deduplication checks;
language detection;
metadata enrichment;
optional OCR and table extraction.

The goal is not to preserve raw bytes, but to preserve meaning.
For a beginner, the key idea is this: different file types break in different ways. A PDF may scramble reading order. An HTML page may include menus and footers that should never become retrieval content. A spreadsheet may depend on row and column labels that plain text loses. That is why data preparation is not one generic “load document” step. It is a set of format-specific fixes.

2.9 Why Text Chunking Matters
Chunking is the process of breaking documents into chunks for retrieval. Chunks that are too small lose context. Chunks that are too large dilute relevance and waste tokens. Chunking is therefore one of the highest-leverage decisions in RAG.
The ideal chunk is not a fixed number of characters. It is a unit of meaning that is also small enough to rank, store, and inject efficiently.
This repository uses a structure-aware chunking baseline instead of blind fixed-width slicing. The core logic tracks headings, groups paragraphs, and creates chunks close to a target length:
def chunk_document(path: str, text: str, target_chars: int = 1100) -&gt; list[dict[str, str]]:
    cleaned = strip_quarto_noise(text)
    lines = cleaned.splitlines()
    chunks: list[dict[str, str]] = []
    heading_stack: list[str] = []
    buffer: list[str] = []

    def flush() -&gt; None:
        nonlocal buffer
        body = "\n".join(line.strip() for line in buffer if line.strip()).strip()
        if not body:
            buffer = []
            return
        title = " &gt; ".join(heading_stack) if heading_stack else Path(path).stem
        paragraphs = [part.strip() for part in re.split(r"\n\s*\n", body) if part.strip()]
        current = ""
        chunk_id = len(chunks) + 1
        for paragraph in paragraphs:
            candidate = paragraph if not current else f"{current}\n\n{paragraph}"
            if current and len(candidate) &gt; target_chars:
                chunks.append(
                    {
                        "chunk_id": f"{Path(path).stem}-{chunk_id}",
                        "source_path": path,
                        "section": title,
                        "text": current.strip(),
                    }
                )
                chunk_id += 1
                current = paragraph
            else:
                current = candidate
        if current:
            chunks.append(
                {
                    "chunk_id": f"{Path(path).stem}-{chunk_id}",
                    "source_path": path,
                    "section": title,
                    "text": current.strip(),
                }
            )
        buffer = []
Even if the code looks simple, it encodes several important design decisions:

headings are preserved as section metadata;
paragraphs are treated as semantic boundaries;
chunk size is controlled, but not by cutting text in arbitrary positions;
each chunk carries source provenance for later display and citation.

This is the main idea of chunking in plain language: keep together what belongs together, and split apart what would otherwise become too long to retrieve well.

3.4 Embedding Model Selection
Model selection should consider:

retrieval quality on representative tasks;
dimensionality and storage cost;
latency and throughput;
multilingual performance;
licensing and deployment constraints.

Benchmarks such as MTEB are useful starting points, but internal evaluation remains essential. The best model is the one that performs reliably on your corpus and query distribution.

3.12 Index Optimization Techniques
Index optimization includes:

selecting the right ANN structure;
tuning recall-latency parameters;
managing vector compression;
partitioning by metadata or tenant;
refreshing stale indexes safely.

The best index is not necessarily the fastest one. It is the one that helps the whole application meet quality and latency targets simultaneously.

4.4 Sparse Retrieval
Sparse retrieval is based more directly on word overlap. Methods such as BM25 give higher scores to chunks that contain important query terms.
This is useful when the user’s wording matters a lot, such as:

product names;
error messages;
abbreviations;
IDs;
exact phrases from documentation.

Sparse retrieval can look old-fashioned compared with embedding-based methods, but it remains very useful because many real user questions contain the exact words that matter.
Its weakness is the opposite of dense retrieval’s weakness. If the wording changes a lot, sparse retrieval may miss clearly related chunks.

4.4 Implementing Hybrid Search
A practical hybrid pipeline might:

retrieve candidates from a dense index;
retrieve candidates from a sparse index;
merge and deduplicate results;
apply re-ranking with a stronger model;
assemble the final context window.

The implementation details vary, but the principle is stable: use cheaper methods for candidate generation and more expensive methods for final ranking.

4.4.1 Practical Example: Dense vs Sparse vs Hybrid
This chapter’s example script, code/cli/retrieval_compare.py, compares three retrieval strategies on the actual book corpus after it has been ingested and indexed:

dense retrieval using the selected embedding model, with bge-m3:latest as the default baseline in this project;
sparse retrieval using a small BM25 implementation;
hybrid retrieval using weighted score fusion.

Run it with:
python3 code/cli/ingest_book.py
python3 code/cli/build_book_index.py --embed-model bge-m3:latest
python3 code/cli/retrieval_compare.py --question "How does the book compare RAG with fine-tuning?" --embed-model bge-m3:latest
The key hybrid scoring logic is simple:
def hybrid_scores(question: str, chunks: list[str], alpha: float) -&gt; dict[int, float]:
    dense = min_max_normalize(dense_scores(question, chunks))
    sparse = min_max_normalize(sparse_scores(question, chunks))
    return {
        index: alpha * dense.get(index, 0.0) + (1 - alpha) * sparse.get(index, 0.0)
        for index in range(len(chunks))
    }
This code highlights an important engineering idea: hybrid retrieval does not have to start with a complicated platform. Even a straightforward weighted merge is enough to show why lexical and semantic signals complement each other when searching a real chapter set.

4.11 Retrieval Pipelines
A retrieval pipeline is often multi-stage:

candidate generation;
filtering;
ranking;
context assembly;
optional citation or provenance tagging.

Seeing retrieval as a pipeline helps teams isolate failure modes and optimize the right layer.

5.4 Prompt Design with Retrieved Context
The prompt is the interface between retrieval and generation.
It tells the model:

what the user asked;
what evidence was retrieved;
how the evidence should be used;
what the model should do if the evidence is weak;
what form the answer should take.

In this project, the prompt builder in code/core/book_rag.py makes those choices explicit:
def build_prompt(question: str, retrieved: list[dict[str, str]]) -&gt; str:
    answer_language = detect_answer_language(question)
    context = "\n\n".join(
        f"[{index}] {item['source_path']} | {item['section']} | score={item['score']:.3f}\n{item['text']}"
        for index, item in enumerate(retrieved, start=1)
    )
    return textwrap.dedent(
        f"""
        You are answering questions about the book project in the local workspace.
        Use only the retrieved context below.
        If the retrieved context is insufficient, say that clearly.
        Give a concise answer in {answer_language}.
        Keep the final citation line in the format "Sources: ...".

        Question:
        {question}

        Retrieved context:
        {context}
        """
    ).strip()
This is a simple prompt, but it already includes several important ideas:

the model is told to answer from retrieved context;
the model is told to admit when context is not enough;
the model is told what language to answer in;
the retrieved chunks are labeled with source information.

That is a good baseline because the generation rules are visible and easy to reason about.

5.6 Framework-Agnostic Structured Generation
The core principles work even without a framework:

assemble relevant context;
state the task clearly;
define output expectations;
validate the response;
log evidence and outcome.

This makes the system easier to reason about and port across runtimes or vendors.

7.3 Graph-Based Retrieval Pipelines
Graph-based retrieval pipelines typically combine:

entity recognition or linking;
graph traversal or neighborhood expansion;
optional text retrieval for supporting descriptions;
ranking over both nodes and passages.

The benefit is deeper reasoning over connected knowledge. The cost is higher modeling and maintenance complexity.

7.5 Toward Next-Generation RAG Systems
Next-generation RAG systems are likely to be adaptive rather than monolithic. They will:

route requests across multiple backends;
combine vector, sparse, structured, and graph retrieval;
use tool calls to verify and enrich evidence;
personalize context assembly by task and user role;
evaluate themselves continuously in production.

The long-term lesson is simple: RAG is not disappearing. It is broadening into a family of grounding strategies for LLM systems. Teams that understand the underlying retrieval problems will be best positioned to build reliable applications as the tooling evolves.

2.2 What Data Preparation Is Trying to Achieve
Before getting into methods, it helps to be clear about the goal.
Data preparation is trying to produce chunks that are:

complete enough to make sense on their own;
small enough to retrieve efficiently;
clean enough to avoid obvious noise;
rich enough in metadata to support filtering and citation;
faithful enough to the source that meaning is not lost.

If a chapter does not explain these goals, chunking and cleaning can sound like arbitrary tricks. They are not arbitrary. They are ways of helping the retriever find the right evidence and helping the generator answer from that evidence.

2.3 Common Ways Data Preparation Fails
It is also useful to know what can go wrong.
Common failures include:

missing content: useful documents were never ingested;
broken parsing: headings, lists, or tables lost their structure;
noisy text: formatting junk overwhelms the real content;
bad chunk boundaries: one idea is split across chunks or unrelated ideas are merged;
weak metadata: the system knows the text but not where it came from;
duplicated content: retrieval keeps surfacing repeated evidence.

These failures matter because they show up later as user-facing problems. A weak answer is often not a model problem first. It is often a corpus problem first.

2.8 Metadata: The Small Details That Matter Later
Metadata is the information attached to a chunk besides the main text.
In this project, useful metadata includes:

the source file path;
the section title;
the chunk id.

In larger systems, metadata may also include:

author;
timestamp;
document type;
product name;
team or business unit;
access level.

Why does this matter? Because retrieval is not only about matching words or embeddings. Sometimes we also need to know where a chunk came from, whether it is recent, whether the user is allowed to see it, or which section should be shown as a citation. Metadata helps the system filter, rank, group, and explain results.
Without metadata, the system may still retrieve text, but it becomes harder to control and harder to trust.

2.14 Different Content Types Often Need Different Handling
One reason data preparation feels hard is that there is no single perfect rule for every source.
Different content types usually need different treatment:

narrative chapters: often split well by headings and paragraphs;
FAQs: often work best with one question-answer pair per chunk;
policy documents: often need clause numbers and headings preserved;
tables: often need headers kept with the values;
code-heavy documents: often need code and explanation kept close together.

This matters because the “best” chunk is not defined only by length. It is defined by whether the chunk still answers a real user question clearly.

2.16 How to Tell Whether Chunking Is Working
At this point, a reader may still ask: how do I know if my chunking is good enough?
Some simple checks help:

when you read a chunk alone, does it still make sense;
when retrieval succeeds, does the chunk contain a full useful answer or only half of one;
when retrieval fails, is the answer split across multiple chunks in an awkward way;
do top results contain too much repeated or overlapping text;
are chunks so long that irrelevant details drown out the useful part.

These are not perfect metrics, but they are practical signals. In early-stage RAG work, manually inspecting retrieved chunks is often one of the fastest ways to improve system quality.
In this repository, the current chunking strategy is intentionally modest. It is a good teaching baseline because the logic is easy to inspect and the tradeoffs are visible. A stronger next version might add:

explicit overlap between neighboring chunks;
special handling for code-heavy sections;
table-aware and list-aware chunking;
metadata tags beyond source path and section;
chunking rules that differ by document type.

That progression matters because data preparation is not finished once the text is “usable.” It improves as the team learns what kinds of retrieval failures the corpus still produces.

2.17 What This Chapter Produces for the Rest of the System
The output of data preparation is not just “clean text.” The real output is a set of retrieval-ready chunks.
Each chunk should ideally have:

text that still makes sense;
a clear source;
a useful section label;
a size that works for retrieval and prompting.

That is the handoff to the next stage of the system. Chapter 3 will build on that handoff by turning these chunks into a searchable index through embeddings and indexing.

3.2 What This Chapter Is Trying to Solve
The main problem is simple: even if the corpus is well prepared, the system still needs a good way to find the right chunks for a new question.
That means this chapter is trying to answer questions like:

how do we represent chunk meaning in a searchable form;
how does the system compare a user question with stored chunks;
what is the difference between an embedding model, an index, and a vector database;
when is a simple local index enough, and when is a bigger system needed.

If Chapter 2 was about making good chunks, Chapter 3 is about making those chunks searchable.

3.4 Embeddings and Their Role in RAG
An embedding is a numeric representation of text. The practical idea is that chunks with similar meaning should end up closer together in that numeric space.
In a RAG system, embeddings are useful because they let us do this:

turn each chunk into a vector;
turn the user question into a vector;
compare those vectors;
rank chunks by similarity.

That is the core of dense retrieval.
The benefit is easy to understand: the system may still retrieve a relevant chunk even when the user does not use the exact same wording as the document.
The limit is also important: embeddings do not “understand” truth. They only encode patterns of similarity learned during training. If the embedding model is weak for the domain, retrieval quality will suffer.

3.5 What an Embedding Model Actually Helps With
It helps to be concrete here.
An embedding model is good at things like:

matching related wording;
handling paraphrases;
finding semantically similar passages;
supporting multilingual or cross-domain matching, if the model is trained for that.

An embedding model is less reliable for things like:

exact identifiers;
strict keyword matching;
small but important wording differences;
structured constraints such as dates, IDs, or access rules.

That is why embeddings are powerful, but not sufficient by themselves.

3.6 How This Project Builds an Index
In this repository, indexing is intentionally simple. After the book is chunked, the system sends each chunk to an embedding model and stores the result in a JSON file.
The key script is code/cli/build_book_index.py, and the core embedding call lives in code/core/book_rag.py:
def ollama_embed(texts: list[str], embed_model: str = EMBED_MODEL) -&gt; list[list[float]]:
    model_name = normalize_cloud_model_name(embed_model) if is_cloud_model(embed_model) else embed_model
    response = ollama_post("/api/embed", {"model": model_name, "input": texts}, model_name=embed_model)
    return response["embeddings"]
That function takes text chunks, sends them to Ollama’s embedding endpoint, and gets back vectors.
The index-building script then stores each chunk together with:

its chunk id;
its source path;
its section;
its text;
its embedding.

So the index is not only a list of vectors. It is a list of vectors tied back to the original chunk content and metadata.

3.7 Why the Current Index Is Simple but Useful
The current design stores embeddings in a JSON file such as code/build/book_index_*.json.
That is not the most scalable design, but it is useful for learning because:

the whole process stays visible;
the stored data is easy to inspect;
there is little hidden infrastructure;
the connection between chunk text and embedding stays obvious.

This is a good baseline for a teaching project. You can see the data, understand the flow, and debug it without needing a separate vector database.

3.9 Why Embeddings Alone Are Not the Whole Story
It is easy to overtrust embeddings once they start working.
But dense retrieval still has common failure cases:

it may miss exact keywords that matter;
it may rank vaguely related text too highly;
it may struggle with codes, IDs, or product names;
it may not respect business rules such as time, tenant, or permissions.

That is one reason hybrid retrieval is useful. Dense retrieval is good at semantic matching. Sparse retrieval is often better at exact term matching. Using both can produce more stable results.
So the right mental model is:

embeddings help the system search by meaning;
they do not remove the need for other retrieval signals.

3.10 How to Choose an Embedding Model
Model choice matters, but it helps to keep the decision grounded.
In practice, you usually care about:

does it retrieve the right chunks on your questions;
does it handle your language mix well;
is it fast enough for your workload;
is the vector size reasonable for storage and latency;
can you run it where you need to run it.

Public benchmarks are useful, but your own corpus matters more. A model that looks strong on a leaderboard may still be awkward for your documents.
For this project, the default embedding model is bge-m3:latest. That is a practical baseline, not a claim that one model is always best.

3.13 FAISS and Local Vector Search
FAISS is a common tool for local vector search. It is often a good next step after a project outgrows a hand-rolled Python loop over JSON embeddings.
Why teams like it:

it is fast;
it supports common vector search workflows;
it is good for experiments and local systems.

Why it does not solve everything:

it is not a full application platform;
metadata handling is more limited than in some managed systems;
production concerns still need extra engineering.

For this project, FAISS would be a natural upgrade because it would keep the learning setup local while making indexing and search more realistic.

3.14 Vector Databases and When They Matter
Vector databases become more useful when the retrieval system needs more than just “store some vectors and search them.”
They matter more when you need things like:

large corpora;
frequent updates;
metadata filtering;
multiple users or tenants;
operational guarantees around persistence and scale.

For a small teaching project, a local index is often enough. For a production system, storage and serving concerns usually become much more important.
This is why it helps to separate two questions:

do I need better retrieval quality;
do I need stronger retrieval infrastructure.

Those are related, but not the same decision.

3.15 Structured Indexing Still Matters
Not everything should be pushed into embeddings.
Some kinds of information are better handled in structured form:

tables;
records with stable fields;
entity lists;
timestamps;
access rules;
graph relationships.

If a user asks for “the latest policy after January 2025” or “all products in category X,” embeddings alone are not enough. Structured fields matter.
This is why strong RAG systems often combine vector search with metadata filters, keyword search, SQL, or other retrieval methods.

3.17 How to Tell Whether Indexing Is Working
As with chunking, a practical question is: how do we know this part is good enough?
Some useful checks are:

do semantically similar questions retrieve the same useful chunks;
do obvious keyword questions still work well;
are clearly relevant chunks missing from the top results;
does changing the embedding model noticeably improve retrieval;
does the system stay fast enough as the corpus grows.

These checks help keep Chapter 3 grounded in behavior rather than turning it into a list of tools.

