recent;
too specific to live reliably inside pretraining alone;
better verified from source material at answer time.

1.6 A Minimal Mental Model
Before getting deeper into the book, it helps to keep one very small mental model in mind:
question
-&gt; find useful evidence
-&gt; give that evidence to the model
-&gt; answer from that evidence
That is the heart of RAG.
Everything else in the book is really about making one of those steps work better:

data preparation helps create better chunks;
indexing helps make them searchable;
retrieval helps find the right ones;
prompting helps the model use them well;
evaluation helps us tell where the process is failing.

3.17 How to Tell Whether the Index Is Working
As with chunking, a practical question is: how do we know this part is good enough?
Some useful checks are:

do semantically similar questions retrieve the same useful chunks;
do obvious keyword questions still work well;
are clearly relevant chunks missing from the top results;
does changing the embedding model noticeably improve retrieval;
does the system stay fast enough as the corpus grows.

These checks help keep Chapter 3 tied to system behavior rather than turning it into a list of tools.

