it misses the chunk with the exact term the user cares about;
it retrieves a broad explanation when the user needed a narrow fact;
it brings back several almost-duplicate chunks instead of complementary evidence.




how do we make chunks searchable?



how do we retrieve the right chunks more reliably?

4.5 Dense and Sparse Fail in Different Ways
This is one of the most useful things to understand in retrieval.
Dense retrieval may fail like this:

it finds chunks that feel semantically related, but miss the exact point;
it overlooks exact terms that matter;
it returns broad conceptual text instead of the most direct evidence.

Sparse retrieval may fail like this:

it misses paraphrases;
it struggles when the user asks in different words from the source text;
it can overvalue repeated keywords even when the chunk is not the best answer.

Because they fail differently, combining them often works better than relying on one alone.

4.6 Hybrid Retrieval
Hybrid retrieval combines dense and sparse signals.
The basic idea is simple:

dense retrieval helps with meaning;
sparse retrieval helps with exact wording;
together they are often more stable.

This project already includes a simple hybrid retriever. It does not need a fancy platform to be useful. Even a basic score merge can make retrieval noticeably better.
The current implementation normalizes the dense and sparse scores, then combines them with a weight:
def hybrid_scores(question: str, corpus: list[dict[str, str]], index_data: dict, alpha: float = 0.65) -&gt; dict[str, float]:
    dense = min_max_normalize(dense_scores(question, index_data))
    sparse = min_max_normalize(sparse_scores(question, corpus))
    all_ids = {item["chunk_id"] for item in corpus}
    return {
        chunk_id: alpha * dense.get(chunk_id, 0.0) + (1 - alpha) * sparse.get(chunk_id, 0.0)
        for chunk_id in all_ids
    }
You do not need to focus on the syntax first. The important idea is that the system is giving part of the decision to semantic similarity and part of the decision to word-level matching.

4.8 Retrieval as a Pipeline, Not One Step
It helps to stop thinking of retrieval as a single search action.
In many systems, retrieval is really a pipeline:

generate candidates;
filter them;
rank them;
assemble the final context.

This mental model is useful because it shows where different tools belong.
For example:

dense and sparse retrieval are often candidate-generation methods;
metadata filtering narrows the search space;
reranking improves final ordering;
context assembly decides what the generator actually sees.

This chapter will keep using that pipeline view.

4.9 Using Metadata to Improve Retrieval
Metadata becomes especially important here.
Suppose the corpus contains:

several versions of a policy;
documents from different teams;
content from different dates;
material the user may or may not be allowed to access.

In those cases, vector similarity alone is not enough. The system may retrieve a chunk that is semantically relevant but wrong for the user’s situation.
Metadata filtering helps prevent that.
Examples include filtering by:

source type;
section;
date;
team;
product;
access scope.

This is one reason Chapter 2 mattered so much. Good metadata gives retrieval more control.

4.14 Retrieval Over Structured Sources
Not every retrieval problem is “search chunks of text.”
Sometimes the right answer lives in:

a table;
a SQL database;
a graph;
a system of records.

In those cases, the retrieval step may need to do something different, such as:

generate SQL;
generate a graph query;
filter structured records by fields.

This still counts as retrieval in the broad sense. The system is still trying to fetch the evidence needed to answer the question. It is just not always using free-text chunk search.
This matters because many people first learn RAG as “embed chunks, retrieve chunks, prompt model.” That is a useful baseline, but not the whole retrieval design space.

read the retrieved evidence;
understand what part of it matters;
answer the user’s question clearly;
avoid inventing unsupported details;
make it obvious where the answer came from.



once retrieval has found evidence, how do we turn that evidence into a grounded answer?

5.2 What Often Goes Wrong at This Stage
Many RAG systems fail here even when retrieval is decent.
Common problems include:

the model ignores part of the retrieved evidence;
the model answers too broadly instead of answering the actual question;
the model fills in gaps with confident guesses;
the answer sounds polished, but is not well grounded in the retrieved text;
citations are missing, vague, or misleading.

This matters because users do not see the retrieval scores first. They see the answer first. If generation is sloppy, the whole system feels unreliable.

5.8 Citation and Source Use
Citations matter because they show the user where the answer came from.
In a RAG system, citations help with:

trust;
debugging;
manual verification;
better user understanding.

This project includes source path and section data in the prompt, and asks the model to end with a Sources: line.
That is a simple pattern, but it already gives the user something concrete to inspect.
Good citations do not only help the reader. They also help the builder. If the answer is weak, source display makes it easier to tell whether the problem came from retrieval or generation.

5.9 The Shape of the Final Answer
Not every RAG answer should be free-form prose.
Sometimes prose is fine. Sometimes the system should return:

a short bullet list;
a table;
a JSON object;
extracted fields;
a ranked set of records.

The right output shape depends on the task.
If the answer is meant for direct user reading, concise prose with citations may be best.
If the answer is meant for another system step, structured output may be safer.
This is an important design choice because the generation layer is part of the product, not just part of the model call.

5.11 Validation Matters
Once the system asks for a structured answer, it can also validate that answer.
This helps answer practical questions like:

did the model include the required fields;
did it include sources;
is the response format valid;
should the system retry or fall back.

Validation is useful because it treats generation as software behavior, not magic.
Even in a simpler project like this one, the idea still matters. The more important the downstream task, the more generation should be checked.

5.12 Frameworks Can Help, but They Do Not Replace Understanding
Frameworks can help with:

prompt templates;
output parsing;
document objects;
chaining steps together.

That can save time.
But there is also a trap here. A framework can hide the most important part of the system:

what evidence was passed;
how it was formatted;
what instructions the model actually received.

So frameworks are useful, but only if the builder still understands the underlying flow.

5.13 Function Calling and Tool Use
Sometimes a RAG system should not stop after generating text. It may need to call a tool.
Examples include:

fetching a fresh record;
opening a ticket;
running a query;
checking a database;
validating a source.

This extends generation into action.
That can be powerful, but it also raises the bar. Once the system can act, it needs stronger controls around:

when tools are called;
what arguments are allowed;
what failures look like;
what the user is allowed to do.

For that reason, it is usually better to first understand grounded answering well before layering in tool use.

turn documents into chunks;
turn chunks into a searchable index;
retrieve candidate evidence;
generate an answer from that evidence.



how do we know whether the pipeline is actually working well?





the right content never entered the corpus;
the chunking made the evidence hard to retrieve;
retrieval found the wrong chunks;
retrieval found good chunks, but generation used them badly;
the answer sounded polished, but did not actually answer the question.

6.8 What a Practical Evaluation Workflow Looks Like
A useful evaluation workflow does not need to be huge at first.
Even a small setup can be valuable if it is repeatable.
A practical workflow usually includes:

a set of representative questions;
some expectation for what good behavior looks like;
visibility into retrieved chunks;
a way to compare runs after changes;
periodic manual review.

This matters more than trying to build a perfect benchmark too early.
The first goal is not to impress anyone with evaluation sophistication. The first goal is to catch regressions and learn where the system is weak.

6.10 What This Evaluation Does Well
The current evaluator is useful because it is:

small;
easy to understand;
tied to the real project corpus;
repeatable across different model choices and retrieval settings.

That means it can catch simple regressions after changes to:

chunking;
retrieval weights;
prompt design;
model selection.

This is already much better than relying only on casual manual testing.

6.11 What This Evaluation Does Not Yet Do
The current evaluator is also limited.
It does not yet measure things like:

whether the retrieved chunk was the best one, only whether an expected chapter appeared;
whether the answer was fully supported, only whether certain keywords appeared;
whether the answer was concise or well structured;
whether citations truly matched specific claims;
whether behavior stayed strong across many query styles.

So the right way to think about it is:

this is a useful regression check;
it is not yet a complete RAG evaluation system.

That distinction matters because simple evaluation is still valuable, as long as we are honest about what it can and cannot tell us.

6.12 Human Review Still Matters
Automated checks are helpful, but they do not replace reading real outputs.
Human review is still important because a person can notice things such as:

the retrieved chunks are technically related, but not the best evidence;
the answer sounds fine, but misses the user’s main need;
the wording suggests more certainty than the evidence supports;
the output format is awkward even though the facts are present.

In early-stage RAG work, a small amount of careful human review often gives more insight than a large pile of weak metrics.

6.14 What to Measure as the Project Grows
As the system becomes stronger, evaluation can grow in stages.
A reasonable path is:

start with a small fixed question set;
inspect retrieval outputs manually;
compare answer quality after changes;
add stronger labels or model-based judgments later;
track failures by category, not only by pass or fail.

This progression matters because it keeps the evaluation system matched to the maturity of the project.

prepare documents;
chunk them;
index them;
retrieve evidence;
generate an answer;
evaluate the result.




when does the baseline approach stop being enough?

7.2 The Limits of a Simple Retrieve-Then-Generate Loop
A simple RAG loop usually looks like this:
question
-&gt; retrieve top chunks
-&gt; put chunks into prompt
-&gt; generate answer
This works well when:

the needed evidence is mostly contained in a few chunks;
the question is direct;
the corpus is mostly text;
the answer does not depend on many connected facts.

It starts to struggle when:

the answer depends on several separate pieces of evidence;
the system needs to reason across relationships, not just paragraphs;
the answer should come from tables, records, or APIs, not only text;
one retrieval method is no longer enough for the kinds of questions users ask.

That is usually the point where architecture needs to become more flexible.

7.4 Multiple Retrieval Backends
As systems grow, it becomes more common that no single retrieval method is enough.
Some questions are best answered by:

vector search over chunks;
keyword search;
metadata filtering;
SQL over tables;
graph traversal;
API calls to live systems.

This leads to an important idea:

advanced RAG is often not one better retriever;
it is often a system that can choose among several retrieval paths.

That is a big shift. The problem changes from “How do I rank chunks?” to “Which retrieval path fits this question?”

7.5 Query Routing
Query routing is the step where the system decides where a question should go.
For example:

a conceptual question may go to vector retrieval;
a question with an exact product ID may go to keyword or structured lookup;
a reporting question may go to SQL;
a relationship question may go to a graph or dependency model.

Routing becomes useful when sending every question to the same retriever starts producing clearly avoidable mistakes.
The benefit is better fit between question type and retrieval method.
The cost is more complexity. Routing logic can fail too, so it should be added when there is a real need, not just because it sounds advanced.

7.6 Knowledge Graphs and Relationship-Centered Retrieval
Text chunks are good at storing explanations, descriptions, and local context.
They are less natural when the main value lies in explicit relationships, such as:

ownership;
dependency;
chronology;
hierarchy;
membership;
causality.

That is where graph-based approaches can help.
A knowledge graph makes entities and relationships explicit. Instead of asking only “Which chunk is semantically similar?”, the system can also ask:

which entities are connected;
what path links these concepts;
what upstream and downstream dependencies exist.

This can be useful when the answer depends more on structure than on prose.

7.7 Graph-Augmented RAG
Graph-augmented RAG does not replace text retrieval entirely. More often, it adds another source of evidence.
A typical pattern might be:

identify key entities in the question;
traverse graph relationships;
retrieve supporting text around those entities;
combine both kinds of evidence for generation.

This can help with questions where text similarity alone is not enough.
The tradeoff is that graph systems require more modeling effort. Someone has to define or extract entities and relationships in a way that stays useful over time.
So graph-based retrieval is powerful, but it should be justified by the task.

7.8 Retrieval Over Live Systems
Another limit of baseline RAG appears when the source of truth is not static text.
Sometimes the answer should come from:

a live database;
an internal API;
a warehouse;
a ticketing system;
a knowledge service that changes often.

In those cases, a chunk-based text index may not be the best source of truth. The retrieval step may need to fetch live data or generate a structured query.
This is one reason modern RAG often overlaps with tool use. The system is not only retrieving passages. It is retrieving evidence from the right system of record.

7.9 Agentic and Multi-Step Retrieval
Some questions are not answered well in one pass.
The system may need to:

retrieve something;
realize more information is needed;
run a second search;
compare results;
then answer.

This is a more agentic style of retrieval.
It can be useful for difficult tasks, but it also creates more room for failure. Each extra step adds latency, complexity, and debugging cost.
That is why multi-step retrieval should usually be a response to a clear problem, not a default habit.

7.10 Personalization and Access Control
As RAG systems move closer to real users, two additional needs often appear:

different users should see different context;
different users may need different answer styles or evidence scopes.

This means the system may need to personalize retrieval and also enforce access rules.
Examples include:

only showing documents from the user’s team;
prioritizing the user’s current project or product area;
filtering out content the user is not authorized to see.

This is another place where metadata and routing become central. Advanced architecture is often less about clever prompting and more about controlled retrieval behavior.

7.11 Observability Becomes More Important as Architecture Grows
The more advanced the retrieval design becomes, the harder it is to debug by intuition alone.
If the system now includes:

multiple retrievers;
routing rules;
tool calls;
graph traversal;
reranking;
context expansion;

then failure can happen in many places.
That is why advanced RAG systems need stronger observability. The team needs to see:

what path the question took;
what was retrieved at each step;
what was filtered out;
what evidence reached the generator;
what the final answer used.

Without that visibility, complexity grows faster than understanding.

7.13 What This Means for This Project
This repository is still a baseline-first project.
That is a strength, not a weakness.
Right now the project is good for learning because:

the pipeline is visible;
the data flow is understandable;
the retrieval logic is inspectable;
the evaluation loop is simple enough to follow.

The next upgrade for this project is probably not a graph system yet. A more natural next step would be things like:

stronger indexing;
better chunking rules;
metadata-aware retrieval;
reranking;
richer evaluation.

Those improvements keep the project understandable while making it more realistic.
Only after the baseline becomes well understood does it make sense to consider larger architectural changes.
